=== Ch3_Intro ===
Chapter 3: Enforcement and compliance. # diagram: enforcement.jpg

This is where the mask slips. Chapters 1 and 2 asked what to restrict. Chapter 3 asks how to make those restrictions stick.

The answer, inevitably, is surveillance.

*   [Age verification questions.]
    -> Ch3_Q39
*   [VPN restriction questions.]
    -> Ch3_VPN_Intro
*   [Phones in schools.]
    -> Ch3_Phones_Intro

=== Ch3_Q39 ===
Question 39 asks:

"To what extent do you agree with this statement: Adults should complete age checks more often, if it means children are safer online."

Strongly agree to Strongly disagree.

*   [That's a leading question.]
    -> Ch3_Q39_Analysis

=== Ch3_Q39_Analysis ===
It's a textbook leading question.

It presupposes that more age checks equals safer children, and asks if the trade-off is worth it. Disagreeing feels like saying you don't care about child safety.

A more honest framing would be: "Adults should submit biometric data, identity documents, or facial scans to private companies more often, even though existing age verification systems have been breached, are biased against certain demographics, and create centralised databases that are attractive targets for hackers."

Same question. Very different response rate.

*   [Have these systems been breached?]
    -> Ch3_Breach_Evidence

=== Ch3_Breach_Evidence ===
Yes. This isn't hypothetical.

70,000 age verification photos were stolen from Discord's third-party verification provider in 2025. Facial recognition systems have documented bias against darker skin tones and women. The GOV.UK One Login system has faced security concerns. [2][3]

And in February 2026, it got far worse. Leaked source code from Persona—the verification provider used by Discord, OpenAI, Roblox, and Reddit—revealed the company ran 269 surveillance checks on every user who submitted ID. Facial recognition against political watchlists. Suspicious Activity Reports filed to US federal agencies. Biometric data retained for up to three years. The company's commercial and government platforms shared the same codebase. [11]

Discord cut ties. But Roblox, Reddit, and others still use Persona. The company that was "just checking your age" was operating a government surveillance pipeline.

The question asks about age checks as if they're as simple as showing ID at a bar. They're not. They're feeding your face into systems you can't see, can't audit, and can't opt out of.

*   [What about Q40-43?]
    -> Ch3_Q40_43

=== Ch3_Q40_43 ===
Questions 40-43 ask practical questions about implementation:

Q40: "What should be considered to make age restrictions effective?"
Q41: "What impacts might come from requiring age assurance across more platforms?"
Q42: "How could age assurance be made more effective?"
Q43: "What should be considered when assessing age verification technologies?"

These are all free-text boxes. They're asking for input on HOW to build the system—assuming the system should be built.

If you believe age verification is the wrong approach entirely, these boxes are where you say so. Don't just answer "how to make it better"—challenge whether it should exist.

Mention on-device parental controls. Mention education. Mention that the infrastructure being proposed has already failed elsewhere. Mention that any age restriction inherently requires age verification, and you oppose both.

